Moving Forward
So we know how to construct a text network with the textnets package,
and how it takes care of the two-mode and network density problems
inherent in document-term matrices. So now what?
Today we will brieﬂy overview some of the formal structural properties we
are often interested in with text networks.
Speciﬁcally, we will go over some popular measures of vertex centrality.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 4 / 37
What is Vertex Centrality?
In network science, centrality is simply a measure of a vertex’s importance
in a graph.
The simplest measure of centrality is called the unweighted degree
centrality: the number of other vertices k that are connected to vertex i.
The unweighted degree for i, d
i

simply:

(Note: we’ll avoid talking about extensions of these centrality metrics to
directed graphs in this class.)

Weighted Degree Centrality for Texts
It’s easy enough to generalize unweighted degree centrality to the case of
a weighted network: simply sum the edge weights rather than just the
number of edges.
In the case of document-by-document and word-by-word one-mode
projections of a two-mode text network, A, the weighted degree centrality
measures the extent to which vertex i (i.e., a document or word) has
strong connections to other documents/words:

Modiﬁed Weighted Degree
You’ll notice that the functions for calculating weighted degree centralities
on the previous slide look a bit more involved than the degree formula
shown earlier.
With weighted networks, we typically want to try and “balance” edge
weights with the number of edges. This is because a high degree centrality
for i in a weighted network can be a combination of two things: a few
vertices with large weights to vertex i, and/or a larger number of vertices
connected to i.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 13 / 37
Modiﬁed Weighted Degree

Skvoretzc 2010:247):

Interpretation
So how do we interpret these weighted degree centralities?
Example: Obama’s speech content was the least distinctive relative to all
of the other speeches—i.e., he had a lot of content overlap with other
speeches. In fact, all of the most recent presidents have the highest degree
centralities. It seems that speeches have begun to look more and more
similar to each other as time passes—almost as if a “SOTU template”
began to emerge.
Another example: “Administration” is one of the most common words
across the speeches. It is not a very distinctive term.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 19 / 37
We can also create subsets of the network to see what the connections
look like between speciﬁc vertices. For example, maybe we want to
address this question: Among the presidents whose speech content is the
most similar to the corpus as a whole, who is most similar to whom?
Run the code from where you deﬁne V(docs.network)$wdegree <-
docs.wdegree down to where you redeﬁne the plotting margins with
par(mar=c(5.1, 4.1, 4.1, 2.1)).

Sub-Network
The vertices are spaced with the Fruchterman-Reingold algorithm, so more
similar vertices are pushed together and dissimilar ones are pushed apart.
Older SOTUs seem to be the most dissimilar among the otherwise high
degree speeches (notice how Nixon, Carter, Kennedy, and Ford are more
orange). The speeches tend to cluster together by time period, suggesting
that speeches written closer together in time are more likely to have
overlapping speech content. The one exception is Bush, but this may be
due to the fact that Bush Sr. and W. Bush are pooled together into one
vertex.

Betweenness Centrality
Another popular centrality metric is known as betweenness centrality.
Betweenness centrality measures the extent to which a vertex bridges
across groups of vertices that are otherwise disconnected from one
another. In terms of text networks, documents with high betweenness
centrality are those texts that blend together themes/content that are
otherwise rarely combined.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 23 / 37
Unweighted Betweenness Centrality
In the unweighted and undirected case, we deﬁne betweenness centrality
for the i
th
vertex as follows:
b
i
=
X
j6=k6=i
p
jk|i
p
jk
(5)
Where p
jk|i
is the number of shortest paths—which we call geodesic
paths—between vertices j and k that pass through i, and p
jk
is the total
number of shortest paths between j and k.
The
p
jk|i
p
jk
answers this question: among all of the shortest paths connecting
j and k, what proportion of them contain i? Sum up this proportion for
every jk pair excluding i , and you’ve got i’s unweighted betweenness
centrality.

Example of Unweighted Degree Centrality
Medici has a large unweighted degree centrality because so many other
families are connected to it. Medici has a large unweighted betweenness
centrality because it is the only point of connection for several families
(Pazzi, Salviati, and Acciaiuoli) into the larger graph. Any resources
acquired through marriage from these three families, then, must pass
through the Medici to get to the other families.

Weighted Betweenness Centrality
Of course, text networks are weighted.
The simplest weighted betweenness centrality follows the same formula as
the unweighted version: instead of summing the shortest paths, you simply
sum the edge weights across those shortest paths.
However, like weighted degree centrality, we have a potential issue. A high
betweenness centrality for any given vertex i in a weighted text network
can be a function of two things: i being on a few shortest paths with large
edge weights, and i simply being on a large number of shortest paths.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 27 / 37
Modiﬁed Weighted Betweenness
We again use a “tuning parameter,” α, that determines how much
emphasis we want to put on edge weights for determining betweenness
centrality. For the document-level projection, we deﬁne the weighted
betweenness for i as (Ospahl et al. 2010:248):
b
D
i
=
X
j6=k6=i
p
wα
jk|i
p
wα
jk
(6)
Where w is the edge weight between j and k and α is our tuning
parameter. When α < 1, we are putting more emphasis on the number of
shortest paths; when α > 1, we are putting more emphasis on edge
weights. textnets sets α to .25.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 28 / 37

Interpration
Taft, McKinley, and Harding seemed to be the most inﬂuential “brokers.”
In other words, they frequently mixed together speech content that was
otherwise not often combined.
Does this conclusion have face validity? You’d need to read through some
of the speeches to get some context and decide for yourself!
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 April 1, 2019 35 / 37
Conclusion
That wraps up our discussion on text networks.
Keep in mind that we barely scratched the surface of network methods for
text analysis. This is a big area, and network science in general is huge!
We could probably devote an entire course to network analysis with texts.
But hopefully this was enough to at least pique your interest.
Next week, we’ll talk about computational text analysis in mixed-methods
applications. There won’t be a technical component. The classes will
be mostly discussion-based, so you’ll need to do the reading in order
to fully participate!
